GM's Guide to the Daedric Path: The Hollow Forgery
This document details the nature, mechanics, and consequences of the dark alternative to a true Dragonborn—a path of stolen power available to both the party and their Rival.
I. The Core Philosophy: The Hollow Forgery
A true Dragon Soul is a star—a perfect, divine fragment of Akatosh's power. It is vast, eternal, and a natural conduit for the Thu'um. It is a solid gold statue, forged by a god.
A mortal soul is a block of exquisite, unique marble—finite, yet dense with the intricate veins of emotion, the detailed features of memory, and the historical weight of experience.
The Daedric ritual is an act of blasphemous sculpture. It uses the metaphysical edge of Mehrunes' Razor to take the block of mortal marble and carve it into the silhouette of the star. To mimic the simple, pure shape of a Dragon's power, the ritual chisels away the complex, "un-dragonlike" parts of the soul. The intricate veins of empathy, the delicate features of compassion, and the historical weight of cherished memories become the marble chips left discarded on the floor. These pieces of humanity are the price of achieving the new shape.
What remains is a forgery. It possesses the correct shape to trick the universe, to channel the Thu'um and absorb a dragon's power. It is a hollowed-out imitation. Having had so much of its original substance carved away, it is a smaller, less substantial soul than the mortal one it began with.
It is a shadow of a Dragon Soul, built from the ghost of a mortal one.
II. The Rival's True Path
The Rival the party meets in Act II is 100% mortal. His extraordinary skill is the result of a lifetime of obsessive, ruthless training. He is a prodigy pushed to the absolute breaking point.
During Act III, as the party seeks the wisdom of the Greybeards, the Rival is on a parallel quest for a shortcut. He is hunting for the components of the soul-carving ritual, desperate to break through the "mortal limit" they have all encountered.
During Act IV, he succeeds. He performs the ritual and becomes a False Dragonborn at the story's climax, arriving at the Time-Wound as a newly-made thing, bearing the fresh spiritual scars of his terrible choice.
III. The Ritual of the Carved Soul
To become a False Dragonborn is to undertake a dark and perilous quest. It requires three components:
The Instrument - Mehrunes' Razor: The ritual requires a tool capable of cutting metaphysical concepts. The Razor is the only artifact known to mortals that can perform this kind of soul-surgery.
The Anvil - A Lorkhan-Touched Site: The ritual must be performed at a place where the veil between the mortal and the divine is thin, a place tied to the creation of mortals (e.g., a Lunar Forge, the Underforge, the Atronach Stone on a specific night).
The Sacrifice - The Renunciation of Self: To carve away your humanity, you must first define it. Each participant must choose a core, defining aspect of their mortal self and offer it to Mehrunes Dagon as the material to be carved away. This is a specific, narrative sacrifice: sacrificing their Honor, their Loyalty, the memory of a loved one. The player must state this sacrifice aloud to seal their damnation.
IV. The Mechanical & Narrative Consequences
Choosing this path grants immense power at a terrible, permanent cost.
The Boon: The Perfect Silhouette
The universe is fooled by the shape of your soul. You gain the functional abilities of a Dragonborn.
Soul Absorption: You can now absorb the souls of slain dragons.
Instantaneous Learning: You can instantly learn Shouts from Word Walls and the Elder Scroll.
The Cost: The Price of the Forgery
You are now a hollow forgery, a brittle vessel holding power it was never meant to contain.
The Hollow Soul (The Lost Substance): Your soul is now fundamentally less than what it was.
Mechanical Effect: You permanently lose 2 points of maximum HP and 2 points of maximum FP. This represents the core substance of your soul that was chiseled away and can never be reclaimed.

The Carved Humanity (The Empathic Void): The most intricate, "human" parts of your soul are gone, leaving only the crude shape of ambition and power.
Mechanical Effect: You suffer a permanent -2 penalty to your Guile Target Number on all Persuasion checks. However, the remaining predatory focus grants you a permanent +2 bonus to your Guile Target Number on all Intimidation checks.

The Sculptor's Mark (The Daedric Taint): The tool used for the carving has left its unholy mark upon your very essence.
Mechanical Effect: You are now considered an "unholy" creature. Divine magic from the Aedra rejects you. Any healing spell or effect from the school of Restoration now deals 1 irreducible damage to you instead of healing.

Soul Dissonance (The Unstable Vessel): Using a Shout is a Major Action that costs no FP. The Soul Dissonance table is the sole cost and limiter of your stolen power. Immediately after you use a Shout, you must roll on the following d20 table.

Soul Dissonance Table (Roll 1d20 - No FP Cost)
1. Perfect Harmony (The One-in-Twenty Miracle)
Effect: The Shout is an automatic Critical Success in its effect (max damage/duration, affects an additional target, etc.). The perfect channeling invigorates you; you gain a temporary +2 bonus to one of your Stat Scores of your choice for the next round. This is the fleeting moment the forgery feels real.
2. Resonant Power (High-Risk, High-Reward)
Effect: The Shout works perfectly. The raw power resonates within you, sharpening your senses. You gain Advantage on your next roll. However, the power lingers, hungry for more. The next time you use a Shout in this combat, you must roll on this table twice and take the worse result.
3. Controlled Force (The Best Normal Outcome)
Effect: The Shout works exactly as intended with no negative side effects. You successfully wrestled the power into submission. (This is now a rare and lucky outcome).
4. Overchannel (Power at a Price)
Effect: The Shout's damage or effect is increased by 50%. However, the immense effort leaves you physically drained. You suffer a level of Exhaustion, giving you a -2 penalty to your Might Target Number until you complete a Short Rest.
5. All or Nothing (A Brutal Trade-Off)
Effect: The Shout works perfectly. However, the sheer focus required leaves you completely exposed. The next attack made against you before your next turn is an automatic hit.
6. Physical Toll (Minor, but Accumulates)
Effect: The Shout works as intended, but the physical strain is significant. Your muscles tear, and you bleed from the effort. You take 2 damage (this can be reduced by armor).
7. Spiritual Bleed (The Core Cost)
Effect: The Shout works as intended, but the effort carves a new hairline fracture in your soul. You take 1 irreducible damage as your own life force is vented in the effort.
8. Destructive Echo (Collateral Damage)
Effect: The Shout works, but the untamed energy explodes from you. All creatures within 10 feet of you (including allies, but excluding yourself) are knocked prone and take 1 irreducible damage from the concussive force.
9. Draining Echo (A Taste of Mortality)
Effect: The Shout works as intended. However, the backlash siphons your mortal energy. You cannot benefit from any HP or FP regeneration (from perks, spells, or abilities) until the end of your next turn.
10. Unsettling Feedback (Mental Strain)
Effect: The Shout works, but the Daedric taint whispers in your mind. You are shaken and unnerved, suffering Disadvantage on all Guile rolls until the end of your next turn.
11. Unstable Power (A Lingering Weakness)
Effect: The Shout works, but your control is slipping. Until the end of the combat, each time you take damage from an enemy, you take an additional 1 damage as the unstable power in your soul amplifies the injury.
12. Arcane Backlash (Scrambled Connection)
Effect: The Shout works as intended. However, the raw force scrambles your connection to conventional magic. You cannot cast spells on your next turn.
13. Warped Shout (Unpredictable Results)
Effect: The Shout's energy is warped. It still hits your intended target, but its effect is twisted. A Fire Breath shout might deal shock damage and drain FP; an Unrelenting Force shout might trap the target in a temporary cage of force. The GM determines the specific warped effect, which may be better or worse than the original.
14. Diminished Power (A Costly Whiff)
Effect: You stumble over the words of power. The Shout is released, but it is a pale imitation of its true potential. Its damage, duration, or effect is halved. The action is largely wasted.
15. Agonizing Recoil (Significant Self-Harm)
Effect: The Shout works, but the recoil is immense. You are thrown backwards 10 feet, knocked prone, and suffer 3 irreducible damage.
16. Errant Shout (Betrayal of Intent)
Effect: The Shout fails to hit your primary target. Instead, it veers off and hits the nearest ally for its full effect. If no allies are in range, it hits you instead.
17. Power Siphon (Empowering the Enemy)
Effect: The Shout fails completely. The energy you gathered is instead absorbed by your intended target. They heal for 4 HP and gain Advantage on their next attack roll.
18. Agonizing Feedback (A Lost Turn)
Effect: The Shout fails completely. The power turns inward, wracking your body with pain. You take 2 irreducible damage and are Staggered, losing your next Major Action.
19. Temporary Fracture (A Gaping Wound)
Effect: The Shout fails. The effort creates a significant fracture in your soul's forgery. You become Vulnerable, meaning you take double damage from all sources until the end of your next turn.
20. Soul Shatter (Catastrophic Failure)
Effect: The forgery cracks catastrophically. The Shout fails, and a wave of pure despair erupts from you. You take 3 irreducible damage, and are Paralyzed, losing your next turn completely as you struggle to hold your very essence together.


